    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-11-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-11-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="223"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d223">
                <head>223. Notes of Meeting<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d223fn1">Source:
                            <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_EGM1">George Elsey</persName> Papers, Van De Mark
                        Transcripts (1 of 2). No classification marking.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1968-11-17">November 17, 1968</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName corresp="#p_EGM1">Elsey</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_WP1"
                            >Warnke</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_GPG1"
                            >Goulding</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_PCRE1">Pursley</persName>
                    </hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> 11:05 a.m.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_LBJ1">LBJ</gloss> call Sun. am./very friendly to <gloss
                        target="#t_LBJ1">LBJ</gloss>.<note n="2" xml:id="d223fn2">At 9:30 a.m. that
                        day, <persName corresp="#p_CCM1">Clifford</persName> called the President at
                        his Texas Ranch. (Ibid., President’s Daily Diary) No record of this
                        conversation has been found.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0692" n="658" xml:id="pg_658"/>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SS1">Symington</persName> called too.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>I.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>1st accomplishment of <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> press
                                conference.<note n="3" xml:id="d223fn3">See <ref target="#d213"
                                    >Document 213</ref>.</note> No doubt in minds of Americans any
                            more since his press conference.</p>
                        <p>S.V.Namese attack on <gloss target="#t_LBJ1">LBJ</gloss> started at time
                            of bomb halt &amp; continued for 12 days.</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>a)</label>
                            <item>—cables show it. They deliberately started a campaign of
                                vilification.</item>
                            <label>b)</label>
                            <item>—Am. newspaper articles such as <persName corresp="#p_BK1">Keyes
                                    Beech</persName> prompted by Saigon.<note n="4" xml:id="d223fn4"
                                    >See <ref target="#d189">Document 189</ref>.</note>
                            </item>
                            <label>c)</label>
                            <item>—intercepts &amp; intelligence showing statements by <persName
                                    corresp="#p_NVT1">Thieu</persName>, <persName
                                    corresp="#p_NCKVP1">Ky</persName> et. al. against <gloss
                                    target="#t_LBJ1">LBJ</gloss>, (e.g. S.Vietnamese amb. to
                                    Seoul<note n="5" xml:id="d223fn5">The South Vietnamese
                                    Ambassador to the Republic of Korea was <persName>Nguyen Van
                                        Kieu</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_NVT1"
                                        >Thieu</persName>’s brother.</note> quoting <persName
                                    corresp="#p_NVT1">Thieu</persName> &amp; <persName
                                    corresp="#p_NCKVP1">Ky</persName> saying <gloss target="#t_LBJ1"
                                    >LBJ</gloss> was engaging in political trickery.</item>
                        </list>
                        <p>‘I happen to <hi rend="italic">know</hi>
                            <gloss target="#t_LBJ1">LBJ</gloss> didn’t end the bombing on 31 Oct.
                            just to elect <persName corresp="#p_HHH1">Humphrey</persName> because
                            I’ve never believed he wanted <persName corresp="#p_HHH1"
                                >Humphrey</persName> to win!” <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss>
                            Sunday 17 Nov. ‘68.</p>
                        <p>
                            <persName corresp="#p_BE2">Bunker</persName> on [November] 11th reported
                            no sense of urgency at all—January is plenty of time to do
                                anything.<note n="6" xml:id="d223fn6">See <ref target="#d214"
                                    >Document 214</ref>.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="italic">Then</hi> came <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss>
                            press conference &amp; <hi rend="italic">overnight</hi> Saigon suddenly
                            became urgent &amp; caught the point.</p>
                        <p>
                            <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss>’s point: Do you wait &amp; let
                            Saigon tear us to pieces—lie, lie, lie—</p>
                        <p>
                            <gloss target="#t_LBJ1">LBJ</gloss> can’t do it. So <gloss
                                target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> decided somebody had to tell the truth— <list>
                                <item>—about <gloss target="#t_LBJ1">LBJ</gloss>
                                </item>
                                <item>—to the Am. people</item>
                                <item>—to the world</item>
                                <item>—to Saigon—i.e. letting <persName corresp="#p_NVT1"
                                        >Thieu</persName>&amp; <persName corresp="#p_NCKVP1"
                                        >Ky</persName> know <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss>
                                    Gov’t is up to their tricks.</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                        <p>The S.V.Namese attacks were unwarranted &amp; dishonest; someone had to
                            answer them &amp; <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> did.</p>
                        <p>All <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> did was stick to facts—no
                            conclusions, no personal vilification—I ascribed no motives—just the <hi
                                rend="italic">facts</hi>.</p>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="italic">Now</hi> there is no doubt in minds of Am. people or
                            the press as to the truth in what happened.</p>
                        <p>This is corroborated by press stories, cartoons &amp; editorials.</p>
                        <pb facs="0693" n="659" xml:id="pg_659"/>
                        <p>
                            <gloss target="#t_GME1">GME</gloss> makes point that <hi rend="italic"
                                >only</hi>
                            <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss>
                            <hi rend="italic">could have done this</hi>. <gloss target="#t_LBJ1"
                                >LBJ</gloss>
                            <hi rend="italic">couldn’t</hi>. State <hi rend="italic">wouldn’t</hi>.
                                <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> was <hi rend="italic">only</hi>
                            one who could &amp; would, &amp; would have <hi rend="italic"
                                >credibility</hi>. (<gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> jumps at
                            this.)</p>
                        <p>Second accomplishment of <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> press
                            conference.</p>
                    </item>
                    <label>II.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>We got Saigon moving. On 29 Oct., at time we first were ready to stop,
                            they balked. They continued to balk, right up to <gloss target="#t_CMC1"
                                >CMC</gloss> press conference.</p>
                        <p>Despite State, <persName corresp="#p_BE2">Bunker</persName>, etc. etc.,
                            nothing was happening.</p>
                        <p>Proof positive: <persName corresp="#p_BE2">Bunker</persName>’s cable of
                            12th 0730 a.m.<note n="7" xml:id="d223fn7">
                                <ref target="#d214">Document 214</ref>.</note> that Saigon is not
                            moving at all &amp; wants to wait until January.</p>
                        <p>&amp; <persName corresp="#p_NVT1">Thieu</persName>’s <hi rend="italic"
                                >brother</hi> told Embassy on some day we need lots of time. Not
                            only weren’t they moving—they had no <hi rend="italic">intention</hi> of
                            moving &amp; were counting to dig up more &amp; more objections.
                            Movement in Saigon started on 14th reported by <persName
                                corresp="#p_BE2">Bunker</persName> “logjam has broken—”</p>
                        <p>Saigon galvanized into activity after “righteous indignation.”<note n="8"
                                xml:id="d223fn8">Telegram 42651 from Saigon, November 14. (<persName
                                    corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> Library, National Security
                                File, Country File, Vietnam, Memos to the President/Bombing Halt
                                Decision, Vol. VI)</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> question—does this sound too
                            self-serving?</p>
                        <p>(<gloss target="#t_GME1">GME</gloss> answer—No—you’re just citing
                            facts.)</p>
                        <p>Now, however, movement has slowed. State is <hi rend="italic">slowing
                                down &amp; softening</hi>.</p>
                        <p>S.V.Namese is trying to <hi rend="italic">test</hi> us by <hi
                                rend="italic">quibbling</hi> over words in a joint statement.</p>
                        <p>
                            <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bui Diem</persName> dashed home &amp; tells
                            everybody to move!!!</p>
                        <p>But they <hi rend="italic">aren’t</hi> moving for last 2-3 days.</p>
                    </item>
                    <label>III.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>Maybe the S.Vamese. <hi rend="italic">Don’t</hi> want to move!!! <list>
                                <label>a)</label>
                                <item>political—the longer they put off, the better SVNam will
                                    be.</item>
                                <label>b)</label>
                                <item>economic—</item>
                                <label>c)</label>
                                <item>military—they’re in No danger at all.</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                        <p>Various reasons to support this: <list>
                                <item>It makes no diff. to SVNam how many Amers are killed.</item>
                                <item>The longer it goes on, the better armed the <gloss
                                        target="#t_ARVN1">ARVN</gloss> will be.</item>
                                <item>549,500 troops pour gold in!!!</item>
                                <item>The ruling clique is incredibly corrupt &amp; shipping gold by
                                    the ton to Swiss banks.</item>
                                <item>The <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> shld. not go on
                                    fighting &amp; dying just for these guys.</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                        <p>All this leads to conclusion we’ll <hi rend="italic">never</hi> come to
                            an agreement with <persName corresp="#p_NVT1">Thieu</persName> &amp;
                                <persName corresp="#p_NCKVP1">Ky</persName> because they <hi
                                rend="italic">Don’t</hi> want agreement!</p>
                    </item>
                    <pb facs="0694" n="660" xml:id="pg_660"/>
                    <label>IV.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>Re the criticism that <gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> broke new
                            ground &amp; made new policy by stating “we’ll go it alone if
                            needed:”</p>
                        <p>—<gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> was merely re-stating a State Dept
                            cable of 8 Nov; &amp; it was re-stated by State 14 Nov in cable &amp;
                            publicly by State same day.</p>
                    </item>
                    <label>V.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>What should our policy be from now on?</p>
                        <p>(<gloss target="#t_CMC1">CMC</gloss> refers to a memo from <persName
                                corresp="#p_HM1">Mort Halperin</persName>
                            <gloss target="#t_GME1">GME</gloss> has not seen.)<note n="9"
                                xml:id="d223fn9">Not found.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Course A—</p>
                        <p>Just continue our present course <hi rend="italic">but</hi> numerous
                            problems <list>
                                <item>—continual erosion on <gloss target="#t_DMZ1">DMZ</gloss>
                                    &amp; on attacks on cities.</item>
                                <item>—growing disaffection in <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss>
                                </item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                        <p>Course B—</p>
                        <p>Postpone talks but hold private talks with Hanoi.</p>
                        <p>Course C—</p>
                        <p>Start expanded talks—holding open a seat for Saigon.</p>
                        <p>He’ll end up <hi rend="italic">Strongly</hi> on Course “C”.</p>
                        <p>Recommended course <list>
                                <item>—Send written message to <persName corresp="#p_NVT1"
                                        >Thieu</persName> setting <hi rend="italic">date</hi> for
                                    talk in Paris</item>
                                <item>—will go with him or without him</item>
                                <item>—we must not permit talks to stall</item>
                                <item>—we must <hi rend="italic">reduce</hi> level of combat &amp;
                                    start troop withdrawal</item>
                                <item>—<gloss target="#t_LBJ1">LBJ</gloss> has borne the brunt—&amp;
                                    must not be cheated out of any credit for: <list>
                                        <item>—for lowering the level of casualties</item>
                                        <item>—no reason why he can’t bring [home] 5-10,000
                                            troops.</item>
                                    </list>
                                </item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
